Knife skills are one of my favorite aspects of cooking. Practicing them may not make for a cool Instagram photo but they remind you of the craftsmanship in cooking and the importance of technique. I’m incredibly grateful to the chefs I worked under that held me to a high standard, always reminding me that my cuts could be better. I think It’s crucial to take joy in the little stuff like Brunoise mirepoix.

Hanging @autumn_olive_farms belly in the fire for our dinner tomorrow with @dannyleedc I’m so excited to share the Korean-Mid Atlantic mash up with everyone. It’s gonna be a blast!

What an absolute joy it was spending time with Mama Lee and @dannyleedc in the @thedabneydc kitchen for our dinner earlier this week.  Every once in a while your lucky enough to spend time with other chefs that truly enjoy cooking and bringing their guests happiness through the food they prepare. Danny and his Mom embody this! And I’m so grateful to have been able to cook over the fire with both of them. We will definitely do it again!

Poisson a la John Haywood from the @petitecerisedc menu. John Haywood was the first serious chef I worked for, culinary school wasn’t in the cards for me so I staged at restaurants to educate myself and John’s restaurant OXO in Charlottesville VA was the first serious one I worked in. He agreed to take me on and train me. I’m incredibly grateful for the knowledge I gained from him and all the other members of the team there. This is one of his dishes and it’s the first one I learned how to make in its entirety, we now serve it as a tribute to him.  Thanks for all the knowledge Chef.

@petitecerisedc Bringing in beautiful whole fish is a crucial part of running our kitchen. Unfortunately there’s more and more cooks that don’t get the opportunity to learn how to butcher either fish or meat. Seeing these animals in the beginning state is a very good way to help young cooks learn about the origins of the product they work with and the importance of understanding and knowing the farmers, fishers, purveyors etc etc who are bringing these items in the door. I have so many fond memories of learning these skills from the chefs I worked for. Please take the time to bring whole items in if you can. Yellowfin Tuna, Sword and Fluke

Exciting News coming soon for Coffee lovers in DC.

On Tuesday, January 23rd, @dannyleedc - chef and co-owner of the award-winning @anjufrc, @chikofrc, @mandudc, and @ieggyou - along with his mother Yesoon Lee (better known as Mama Lee), will join Chef @jjlthedabney + team at The Dabney for a one-of-a-kind evening.

This tasting menu will feature collaborative dishes that reflect Danny and Yesoon’s Korean heritage alongside Jeremiah’s Mid-Atlantic cuisine and techniques – all executed and enhanced by The Dabney’s renowned hearth. 

We’ll be offering an eight-course tasting menu in our dining room and a four-course prix fixe at the bar.  Click through our bio link to secure your reservation.
